The paper proposes a game-theoretic model for interdependent scheduling, which suggests that it could belong to the Game Theory (cs.GT) sub-category. The problem of planning and coordinating large-scale infrastructures also suggests that it could belong to the Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing (cs.DS) sub-category. The use of AI techniques for computing best responses and Nash equilibria suggests that it could belong to the Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI) sub-category. The consideration of welfare maximization and Nash dynamics suggests that it could belong to the Systems and Control (cs.SY) sub-category. Finally, the use of machine learning techniques for computing Nash equilibria suggests that it could belong to the Machine Learning (cs.LG) sub-category.
